<p></p>.<p>Cold sensations to the fingers can come from poor circulation, disorders of the nervous system, cold exposure, 
<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/raynauds_phenomenon/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Raynaud's 
phenomenon</a>, and low <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/thyroid_pictures_slideshow/article.htm" rel="slide" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">thyroid</a> condition (<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/hypothyroidism/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">hypothyroidism</a>). Cold fingers may be associated with</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCE:<br><br>Kasper, D.L., et al., eds. <i>Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine, 19th Ed</i>. United States: McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.</p>